        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued March 31 at 3:13AM EDT by NWS Charleston WV</headline>
        <description>At 312 AM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from 6 miles west of Gassaway to
Amherstdale-Robinette. Movement was east at 40 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 40 mph.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects.

Locations impacted include...
Van, Thurmond, Pax, Glasgow, Indore, Little Birch, Stickney, Drennan,
Erbacon, Summersville, Widen, Clay, Frametown, Ansted, Pratt, Wilsie,
Montgomery, Canvas, Birch River, and Prosperity.

This includes the following highways...
Interstate 79 between mile markers 44 and 60.
West Virginia Turnpike between mile markers 47 and 82.
Route 19 between mile markers 1 and 68.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.

A Severe Thunderstorm Watch remains in effect until 600 AM EDT for
central, southern, southeastern and north central West Virginia.</instruction>
